    <p>First blog post! For this blog post i would like to talk about vario=
us issues around linters which exclusively use ASTs (Abstract Syntax Tree) =
for linting source code, and a tree representation you may not know about. =
Over many months of working on a JavaScript linter in rust called <a href=
=3D"https://github.com/RDambrosio016/RSLint/tree/dev">rslint</a> i have enc=
ountered numerous issues and have explored many concepts which i feel i sho=
uld share to offer insights into why i believe purely AST based linting is =
unfit for complex linters.</p>

<p>This post mostly refers to the issues with pure typed AST based linting =
in statically typed languages such as rust, However, most of the issues occ=
ur in dynamically typed languages too.</p>

<p>I will be giving a small introduction to how linters work, feel free to =
skip to the <a href=3D"https://rdambrosio016.github.io/rust/2020/09/18/pure=
-ast-based-linting-sucks.html#problems-with-asts">Problems with ASTs</a> if=
 you already know how linters work.</p>

