<p>This way of using a visitor means each rule is actually made up of two s=
tructs, and the second struct needs to store an <code class=3D"language-pla=
intext highlighter-rouge">Arc&lt;Context&gt;</code> to be able
to add diagnostics. This further introduces more issues i won=E2=80=99t get=
 deep into but they include requiring the diagnostics vector in the context=
 to be locked (through a mutex) to add a diagnostic, and not being able to =
cleanly refer to each rule=E2=80=99s diagnostics/outcome.</p>

<h3 id=3D"bottom-up-rule-checking">Bottom-up rule checking</h3>

<p>Bottom-up rule checking is impossible, which many rules benefit greatly =
from, such as <a href=3D"https://eslint.org/docs/rules/no-await-in-loop"><c=
ode class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">no-await-in-loop</code><=
/a>.
This is because a node cannot know about its parent, swc=E2=80=99s visitor =
attempts to slightly get around this with a <code class=3D"language-plainte=
xt highlighter-rouge">_parent: &amp;dyn Node</code> on ever visitor functio=
n which is a simple wrapper on top of <a href=3D"https://doc.rust-lang.org/=
std/any/trait.Any.html"><code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge=
">Any</code></a>. This still does not allow for recursive bottom-up checkin=
g, and it introduces the mess of needing to downcast the parent.</p>

<p>The fact that bottom-up rule checking is impossible means every rule mus=
t be a bottom-down check, which is usually ugly for the following reasons:<=
/p>

<ul>
  <li>Oftentimes a rule wants to check a node, but only if its the child of=
 a specific node, which requires explicit handling of each possible parent =
(see: <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">no-extra-boolean=
-cast</code>)</li>
  <li>It results in duplicate code for each parent</li>
</ul>

<p>Proof of this can be found in deno_lint=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://git=
hub.com/denoland/deno_lint/blob/master/src/rules/no_await_in_loop.rs">imple=
mentation</a> of <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">no-aw=
ait-in-loop</code>, which is 182 lines, versus rslint=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"=
https://github.com/RDambrosio016/RSLint/blob/dev/rslint_core/src/groups/err=
ors/no_await_in_loop.rs">implementation</a> which is 35 lines.</p>

<h2 id=3D"no-easy-access-to-tokens-or-child-nodes">No easy access to tokens=
 or child nodes</h2>

<p>ASTs are lossy, like the name implies, this means that it is impossible =
to straight from a node to its tokens. It may seem like a small issue but i=
n reality it poses a ton of issues, these include, but are not limited to:<=
/p>

<ul>
  <li>No lexical equality (counting <code class=3D"language-plaintext highl=
ighter-rouge">foo. bar</code> and <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlig=
hter-rouge">foo.bar</code> as the same expression)</li>
  <li>No simple implementation of individual token based rules</li>
  <li>No easy syntax highlighting without reinvoking the lexer</li>
  <li>No easy way to refer to an individual token for pretty errors</li>
</ul>

<p>To get around this, tools like ESLint store the tokens in a store then h=
ave methods on a context object to get the tokens. As you can probably gues=
s, this brings about more issues:</p>

<ul>
  <li>No interning, which can make storing tokens expensive for things like=
 <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">let</code>, <code cla=
ss=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">var</code>, etc.</li>
  <li>Another thing to implement and maintain.</li>
  <li>Tokens don=E2=80=99t know about their parent AST nodes .</li>
  <li>cont: Tokens cannot traverse their siblings, next tokens, prev tokens=
, etc.</li>
  <li>No whitespace and comment tokens, which results in ugly handling of c=
omments and comment directives.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id=3D"lossy">Lossy</h2>

<p>ASTs are lossy, this makes stylistic linting pretty challenging, and it =
often involves digging back into the source code to get whitespace. Not onl=
y is this ugly, it is inefficient and impractical. With a lossless syntax t=
ree we can simply crawl the tree and search for whitespace tokens (which in=
clude all whitespace). As mentioned above, tokens also can crawl tokens bef=
ore them, and even their parent. We can then refer back to these tokens in =
pretty errors to make fixing errors even easier for the user.</p>

